  "opinion": "As a nurse with a bachelor's degree in a city like Bologna where I've seen firsthand the diverse backgrounds of my patients, I've witnessed how stereotype threat can silently undermine potential in STEM fields. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group, leading to anxiety that hinders performance—especially for women and people of color in science and technology. In my practice, I've seen young women hesitate to pursue engineering because they fear being labeled 'not good at math,' even though many of them excel in problem-solving. This isn't just a theoretical issue; it's a real barrier that affects career choices and educational outcomes. Addressing it requires systemic change, not just awareness. Schools should integrate inclusive curricula that highlight diverse scientists and engineers from all backgrounds. Mentorship programs paired with role models who reflect students' identities can build confidence. Additionally, creating safe spaces for discussion in classrooms and workplaces where students feel they can express doubts without judgment is crucial. I believe we must also challenge the implicit biases of educators and peers through ongoing training. As someone who values community and empathy—traits I've cultivated through my nursing career—this work is deeply personal to me. It's about ensuring every child, regardless of their background, feels capable of contributing to STEM. In Bologna, where our community is rich with cultural diversity, this approach aligns with our shared values of inclusion and mutual respect. Without action, stereotype threat will continue to limit the talent pool in STEM, leaving many brilliant minds untapped.",
